âœ¤ Abstraction in Java
â†¬ Abstraction is an object-oriented programming (OOP) concept that focuses on what an object does rather than how it does it. It hides implementation details and exposes only essential functionality to the user.
In Java, abstraction is achieved using:
â¥Abstract Classes
â¥Interfaces

1. Abstract Class
An abstract class is a class that cannot be instantiated. It may contain:
â£ Abstract methods (without body)
â£ Concrete methods (with body)
â£ Variables, constructors

â— Syntax
abstract class ClassName {
    abstract void methodName(); // abstract method

    void normalMethod() {
        System.out.println("Normal method");
    }
}

Example:-
abstract class Vehicle{
abstract void Car(); // abstract method
void fule(){
System.out.println("Used to fule Start Car");
 }
}
class Bike extends Vehicle(){
 @Override
void Car(){
System.out.println("Car Colour is very nice");
}

public static void main(String [] args){
Vehical v= new Car();
v.Car();
v.fule();
 }
}

â˜… Key Points (Abstract Class)
â–º Cannot create object directly
â–º Can have both abstract and non-abstract methods
â–º Supports constructors
â–º Supports inheritance using extends

2. Interface
â® An interface is a blueprint of a class. It contains:
â® Abstract methods (by default)
â® public static final variables
â® Default and static methods (Java 8+)

â— Syntax
interface InterfaceName {
    void methodName(); // public and abstract by default
}

Example:-
interface Animal {
    void sound();
}

class Dog implements Animal {
    @Override
    public void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal a = new Dog();
        a.sound();
    }
}

â˜… Key Points (Interface)
â® Cannot create object
â® Supports multiple inheritance
â® All methods are public abstract by default
â® Variables are public static final

âŠ› Abstract Class vs Interface
| Feature      | Abstract Class      | Interface                         |
| ------------ | ------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| Methods      | Abstract + Concrete | Abstract (default/static allowed) |
| Variables    | Any type            | `public static final`             |
| Inheritance  | Single              | Multiple                          |
| Constructors | Yes                 | No                                |
| Keyword      | `extends`           | `implements`                      |
